Subject Verification: Manually Testing using POSTman or CURL

Last updated: Feb 24th, 2024

Topics: Manual Testing, POSTman, CURL

Finally, to ensure that your code works, you’ll going to need to verify it somehow. This is the realm of the Subject Verification essential. For your assignment, this’ll be simple. You can use either CURL or POSTman to Manually Test your API.

Lesson goals

In this lesson, we’ll cover:

  • Why manual testing can be helpful (but why it doesn’t scale very well)
  • My recommendations for manual testing

Essential in Focus: Subject Verification

Before we begin, let’s recall what Subject Verification is all about.

Subject Verification is about testing.

And we’re only going to be going even heavier on the testing as we progress.

Why? Well, everything is a Guess, right?

Subject Verification is specifically about verifying some aspect of your system — be it a simple function, a class, a method, just the database connection, or the entire system as a whole.

The subject represents what is under test.

In this lesson, we’re primarily going to be concerned with testing the API.

That means, we’re going to be verifying the entire system from End to End, where the testing boundaries wrap around your Vertical Slices — your API calls.

About manual testing

Manual testing is exactly what it sounds like.

You manually test your APi.

I’m sure you’re familiar with this, because how else would you know your API worked?

Using POSTman

When I first started out, I used to use POSTman religiously for testing my APIs.

It’s changed a lot over the years, moving from being just a desktop app to a fully-fledged platform.

For what we’re doing here, it’s probably a bit overkill, but if you’ve never used it, probably good to give it a go.

Alternatives

There are a bunch of other tools you can use out there, like

  • Paw — for Mac
  • Insomnia — pretty popular as of the time of writing this

But honestly, when I can, I just try to use CURL because it’s quick, easy, and as you’ll see in Best Practice-First, when I test my API calls, I prefer to do that using Automated Tests that are actually a part of the codebase itself.

Manually testing w/ CURL

CURL is simple. CURL is nice.

Once your server is up and running, we can test the functionality like this:

CURL command example

curl -X POST -H "Content-Type: application/json" -d '{
  "email": "example@example.com",
  "firstName": "John",
  "lastName": "Doe",
  "username": "johndoe2"
}' <http://localhost:3000/users/new>

curl <http://localhost:3000/users?email=example@example.com>

This command demonstrates how to:

  1. Create a user using the users/new API endpoint
  2. Get that same user by email using the users endpoint with the email param

You can write scripts like that in a file, quickly copy ‘em into your terminal and see how it goes.

🌀 If you’re on Windows, curl isn’t installed by default. Here’s an article you can use to get that setup on your machine.

FAQ

What’s the problem with manual testing?

From a Feedback Loop perspective, the main reason why it’s problematic to do manual testing and manual testing only is because you don’t have tight enough feedback loops.

How often would you forget to open up POSTman and run the tests?

How long would it take to run all those tests if you have a lot of them?

I mean, most of the time, when an application moves towards becoming more valuable, it’s only getting more and more features, right?

That only means more and more tests, more and more things to manually remember, more and more use cases, user stories, and API calls to call with more and more types of data.

Yes, it’s time consuming, and yes, the API tools like POSTman can be pretty good for testing E2E, but the reality is… If you don’t have more a refined testing strategy of different types of tests to act as safeguards, you might find it harder to identify or isolate the part of your codebase that’s broken previously written features and functionality.

Been there. It sucks.

But what if we have a QA team? They’re the ones that handle testing

Look, don’t shoot the messenger here.

I’m merely distilling down what I’ve learned from the experts. I can guarantee if you ask Dave Farley, Kent Beck or Robert Martin, they will all tell you the same thing.

Whoever writes the code should be the same person that tests the code.

And they’d probably even take it a step further to say: you should be using automated tests to guide your designs.

We’ll learn all about this and how to do it in Best Practice-First.

Your Turn!

That does it.

If you’ve implemented all of the API calls, go through them using CURL or POSTman using the grading checklist in the assignment milestone page before continuing.
